WEBVTT

00:09.693 --> 00:11.994
All right,
all right.

00:11.996 --> 00:13.161
Listen up, everyone.

00:13.163 --> 00:15.864
I know most of you
are wondering how the hell

00:15.866 --> 00:17.900
in the world Russ Vandenberg

00:17.902 --> 00:19.200
got promoted

00:19.202 --> 00:20.335
to Detective First Grade.

00:20.337 --> 00:21.937
I've been wondering

00:21.939 --> 00:23.571
the same thing myself. So,

00:23.573 --> 00:25.840
given the hook I have
down at One PP,

00:25.842 --> 00:28.275
Commissioner Reagan.

00:29.478 --> 00:30.978
Careful, I'm
taking names.

00:31.814 --> 00:34.448
The commissioner,
he gave me this.

00:36.753 --> 00:37.818
It's blank, Reagan.

00:38.755 --> 00:39.920
It's not blank,

00:39.922 --> 00:40.987
it's invisible ink.

00:40.989 --> 00:42.355
What it says
is that

00:42.357 --> 00:44.758
though the proud people
of Russ's Dutch heritage

00:44.760 --> 00:46.225
have been
around New York

00:46.227 --> 00:48.461
since day one,

00:48.463 --> 00:50.730
but they've
actually been

00:50.732 --> 00:54.233
underrepresented
amongst the ranks of the NYPD.

00:54.235 --> 00:56.135
Which could be
a problem if, say,

00:56.137 --> 00:57.202
you need someone to hold back

00:57.204 --> 00:59.404
a flood by sticking a finger
in a dike.

01:00.174 --> 01:01.139
So,

01:01.141 --> 01:02.007
the commissioner

01:02.009 --> 01:03.809
has personally
instituted

01:03.811 --> 01:05.477
an affirmative action
program

01:05.479 --> 01:06.812
and Russ

01:06.814 --> 01:08.447
- is our official poster boy.
- Yeah!

01:11.552 --> 01:13.818
To Detective First Grade
Russ Vandenberg.

01:13.820 --> 01:15.853
<i>- Proost!</i>
<i>- Proost!</i>

01:15.855 --> 01:18.056
Thanks, man.

01:18.058 --> 01:19.991
Congrats.

01:27.734 --> 01:28.866
Ellen?

01:30.203 --> 01:31.167
Why don't you come in?

01:31.169 --> 01:33.136
I'm gonna wait out here.

01:33.138 --> 01:35.271
For what?

01:35.273 --> 01:36.707
Russ.

01:36.709 --> 01:38.475
He won't return
my calls or texts.

01:38.477 --> 01:39.743
What's wrong?

01:39.745 --> 01:43.580
You know anything about AA?
The 12 Steps?

01:43.582 --> 01:44.781
I know enough.

01:44.783 --> 01:47.250
Steps eight and nine are:

01:47.252 --> 01:48.618
“identify who you hurt

01:48.620 --> 01:51.721
because of your drinking
and make amends.”

01:51.723 --> 01:55.057
Right. And that's what you want

01:55.059 --> 01:56.792
to do with Russ tonight?

01:56.794 --> 01:59.528
An innocent woman is in prison

01:59.530 --> 02:02.264
on account of a questionable
collar we made.

02:02.266 --> 02:04.399
He needs to help me
set it right.

02:04.401 --> 02:07.568
He's had a few to drink,
he's celebrating.

02:07.570 --> 02:10.071
You're never gonna get what
you want out of him tonight.

02:10.073 --> 02:12.841
We have to set this right.
Me and him.

02:12.843 --> 02:14.175
And you will.

02:14.177 --> 02:16.544
Maybe tomorrow. Okay?

02:16.546 --> 02:18.113
Not tonight.

02:20.117 --> 02:21.649
Now let me drive you home.

02:23.886 --> 02:25.919
Come on.

02:29.258 --> 02:30.691
So, you've given us, what,

02:30.693 --> 02:33.360
five places you don't want
your retirement party.

02:33.362 --> 02:36.229
Six, if you count go-kart racing
in Jersey City.

02:36.231 --> 02:37.564
Oh, Garrett just
threw that one in

02:37.566 --> 02:39.032
'cause he knows
you like to go there.

02:39.034 --> 02:40.466
I don't want a retirement party.

02:40.468 --> 02:42.802
You got to. Think of all
the guys you'd be letting down.

02:42.804 --> 02:44.637
It's just one of those things
you got to do.

02:44.639 --> 02:46.505
I don't want to retire.
It is what it is,

02:46.507 --> 02:48.675
you might as well go out with
a bang and an open bar, right?

02:48.677 --> 02:50.342
I'm afraid I'm not gonna be
as easy as that.

02:50.344 --> 02:51.744
- Oh.
- Travis.

02:51.746 --> 02:52.545
It's mandatory.

02:52.547 --> 02:53.980
The eve of your 63rd birthday.

02:53.982 --> 02:56.748
It's a civil rights violation,
if it came to that.

02:56.750 --> 02:58.717
Not that it's gonna
come to that.

02:58.719 --> 03:00.786
Well, then,
you're making an exception.

03:00.788 --> 03:02.054
Oh, come on,
how many

03:02.056 --> 03:03.055
exceptions have I given you?

03:03.057 --> 03:04.122
What do you mean?

03:04.124 --> 03:05.490
It means you're long
over your limit.

03:05.492 --> 03:07.392
Well, name one.
This, for one thing.

03:07.394 --> 03:08.459
I get razor bumps.

03:08.461 --> 03:10.662
But I never asked
for a doctor's note.

03:10.664 --> 03:13.430
Name one real exception.

03:15.267 --> 03:18.769
Travis, you do not want
to walk out the door

03:18.771 --> 03:20.370
kicking and screaming.

03:20.372 --> 03:22.372
What if it was you, Frank?

03:22.374 --> 03:24.474
What if they tossing you
to the curb, what,

03:24.476 --> 03:26.711
because of some date
on your birth certificate?

03:26.713 --> 03:30.180
Not an issue for me,
I'm not a cop anymore.

03:30.182 --> 03:32.115
Then it is an issue.

03:32.117 --> 03:33.282
You're a good top cop because

03:33.284 --> 03:36.619
you can still walk miles
in a cop's shoes.

03:40.391 --> 03:42.892
He knows we cut corners.
We talked about it,

03:42.894 --> 03:46.029
agreed not to bring up
the problem with the case

03:46.031 --> 03:48.430
unless anyone asked
and no one did.

03:48.432 --> 03:52.367
And this directly led to this
Cerise Paxton's conviction?

03:52.369 --> 03:53.736
Yes.

03:53.738 --> 03:56.739
She had a long record already.
Russ painted it as one of those

03:56.741 --> 03:59.674
“you know she's guilty
of something” things.

03:59.676 --> 04:02.277
He wanted that murder collar,
he was in a hurry up the ladder.

04:02.279 --> 04:03.511
And you?

04:03.513 --> 04:06.347
I was drinking
a quart of vodka a day

04:06.349 --> 04:07.782
and eating oxys
like peanuts.

04:07.784 --> 04:09.617
I needed him to cover me.

04:09.619 --> 04:11.986
There's not a cop in the world,
at least none that I know,

04:11.988 --> 04:13.821
who are gonna give up
their entire career

04:13.823 --> 04:15.156
over one questionable collar.

04:15.158 --> 04:16.357
You would.

04:16.358 --> 04:18.459
If the person went away
for a murder

04:18.461 --> 04:20.894
they didn't commit.

04:20.896 --> 04:22.662
Look, you want my advice?

04:22.664 --> 04:25.098
If you really want to press
this, you're gonna have to

04:25.100 --> 04:26.900
talk to Internal Affairs.
Maybe they'll listen.

04:26.902 --> 04:29.770
I don't want to jam Russ up.
I just want to make this right.

04:29.772 --> 04:33.140
I don't think you can get one
without the other.

04:33.142 --> 04:36.109
Okay, Danny.

04:36.111 --> 04:38.177
Thanks anyway.

